<br>
the best way to spell it would probably be so-u-vi-a (yes, for vi, you put the 'u' character with the 2 dots, followed by a small 'i'), check the polykarbon for the character translations, should be 5 characters long<br>
<br>
edit: the 'l' sound in japanese is usually translated by replacing it with a double vowel, which explains the &quot;u&quot;.  i know i said double vowel, so if you are wondering why 'u' and not 'o' is because double 'o' in japanese is spelled 'ou', or in this case 'sou'.  when pronounced, however, it is said like &quot;soo&quot;. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udraygonroyale2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Draygon Royale2</A> at: 6/6/01 11:53:00 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ulacos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lacos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/8/01 12:42:52 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What are the characters for...</span><hr size=1> I've seen both methods when translating the letter 'V', maybe that works better. Also, soul is &quot;souru&quot;, rather than &quot;soru&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umatrixmccloud.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Matrix McCloud</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www16.brinkster.com/matrixmccloud/m.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/8/01 12:54:56 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www16.brinkster.com/matrixmccloud/Sig.gif width=103 height=116></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What are the characters for...</span><hr size=1> the thing is, the v in japanese is STILL pronounced b no matter which way you spell it. The same as spanish.... <p><hr><br>
